Harness the Power of Elixir and Phoenix LiveView to Send Free Emails with the Gmail API

Punniyakodi

·

Follow

4 min read
·
Jul 7, 2024

I’ll walk you through sending emails from your Phoenix application using the Gmail API. This method allows you to send emails for free, making it an excellent solution for small to medium-sized projects.

For those who want to see the complete code or need a reference implementation, you can check out the full project on GitHub: Phoenix Gmail API Mailer Project

Prerequisites

Before we begin, make sure you have the following:

1. A Phoenix LiveView application set up
2. A Google account
3. Basic knowledge of Elixir and Phoenix

Step-by-Step Guide

1. Understanding Swoosh and Gmail Integration

First, familiarize yourself with how to integrate Gmail with your Phoenix application using Swoosh. You can find detailed documentation here.

2. Set Up Google Cloud Project

2.1. Go to the Google Cloud Console.
2.2. Create a new project and give it a name.
2.3. Once created, select your project from the project selector dropdown menu.

3. Enable the Gmail API

3.1. In your project, navigate to “APIs & Services” > “Library”.
3.2. Search for “Gmail API” and click on it.
3.3. Click the “Enable” button to activate the API for your project.

4. Configure OAuth Consent Screen

4.1. Go to “APIs & Services” > “OAuth consent screen”.
4.2. Choose “External” as the user type (unless you’re using Google Workspace).
4.3. Fill in the required information:
— App name
— User support email
— Developer contact information
4.4. Add the necessary scopes:

https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.compose * Refer to the documentation in (step 1)

4.5. Add test users (including your own email) if you’re using external user type.

5. Create OAuth 2.0 Credentials

5.1. Go to “APIs & Services” > “Credentials”.
5.2. Click “Create Credentials” > “OAuth client ID”.
5.3. Choose “Web application” as the application type.
5.4. Add authorized redirect URIs (e.g., `http://localhost:4000` for development).
5.5. Click “Create” and download the credentials JSON file.

6. Obtain Refresh Token

6.1. Use a tool like Postman(API service tool) and follow the Google OAuth 2.0 documentation to obtain an initial refresh token.

6.2. Make sure to specify the correct scope:

https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.compose * Refer to the documentation in (step 1)

7. Set Up Your Phoenix Project

Add the required dependencies to your mix.exs file:

def deps do
  [{:mail, "~> 0.3.1"}, {:hackney, "~> 1.20"}] * Refer to the documentation in (step 1)
end

Run the below command to install the new dependencies.

mix deps.get

8. Create Token Fetcher Module

Create a new file lib/your_app/token_fetcher.ex with the following content:

defmodule YourAPP.TokenFetcher do

 def get_access_token() do
  body =
   Jason.encode!(%{
    "client_id" => #[Client ID] * Get the Client ID from the JSON file (step 5) 
    "client_secret" => #[Client Secret] * Get the Client ID from the JSON file (step 5)
    "grant_type" => "refresh_token" * grant_type should always be "refresh_token"
    "refresh_token" => #[refresh_token] * Get the refresh_token from (step 6)
   })
 "<h1>Welcome!</h1><p>Thank you for joining our Phoenix app. We're excited to have you on board!</p>"
 body
 |> request()
 |> response()
 |> access_token()
 end

 defp response({:ok, %Finch.Response{body: body}}) do
  Jason.decode!(body)
 end

 defp request(body) do
  headers = headers()
  Finch.build(:post, "https://oauth2.googleapis.com/token", headers, 
  body)
  |> Finch.request(YourAPP.Finch)
 end

 defp headers do
  [{"content-type", "application/json"}]
 end

 defp access_token(body) do
  Map.get(body, "access_token")
 end
end

Replace YourApp with your actual application name, and fill in your client ID, client secret, and refresh token.

9. Configure Mailer

Add the following to your config/config.exs:

config :your_app, YourApp.Mailer,
 adapter: Swoosh.Adapters.Gmail

Important Configuration Note:

In your `config/dev.exs` file, comment out the following line:

# config :swoosh, :api_client, false

This allows Swoosh to use the proper API client in your development environment, ensuring emails are sent correctly during local testing.

10. Create a Mailer Module

A Mailer module is usually created by default when setting up your Phoenix application. If it’s not, create a new file lib/your_app/mailer.ex with the following content:

defmodule YourApp.Mailer do   
 use Swoosh.Mailer, otp_app: :your_app 
end

11. Implement Email Sending

In your LiveView module (e.g., lib/your_app_web/live/index.ex), add the following:

defmodule YourAppWeb.SendMailLive.Index do
 use YourAppWeb, :live_view
 
 import Swoosh.Email
 
 alias YourApp.TokenFetcher
 
 def render(assigns) do
  ~H"""
  <.button phx-click="send">Send Mail</.button>
  """
 end
 
 def handle_event("send", _params, socket) do
  email =
  new()
  |> to("reciver@gmail.com")
  |> from("sender@gmail.com") * Use the same email as your Google Cloud project
  |> subject("Welcome to Our Phoenix App!")
  |> html_body("<h1>Welcome!</h1><p>Thank you for joining our Phoenix app. We're excited to have you on board!</p>")
  
  YourAppWeb.Mailer.deliver(email, 
  access_token: TokenFetcher.get_access_token()) * Refer to the documentation in (step 1)
  
  {:noreply, socket}
 end
end

Replace YourApp and YourAppWeb with your actual application names. Also, update the email addresses and content as needed.

Testing Your Email Sending

1.Start your Phoenix server with mix phx.server.
2. Navigate to the page with your “Send Mail” button.
3. Click the button to trigger the email sending process.

If everything is set up correctly, you should see the email in the recipient’s inbox shortly.

Conclusion

Congratulations! You’ve successfully integrated the Gmail API with your Phoenix application to send free emails. This approach is perfect for small to medium-sized projects that need email functionality without the cost of a dedicated email service.

Also, be mindful of Gmail’s sending limits to avoid any issues with your account.

If you have any questions, or problems, or need further clarification on any part of this tutorial, feel free to reach out to me at: punniyakodi.man@gmail.com

Happy coding!
